column50:
1. Data cleaning is usually the first step in preparing a data analysis pipeline. Treating unstructured data and making it useful for analysis involved a lot of thought process. Right choice of tools is the remedy for this.
2. In the data modelling phase, there is always a risk that the model might overfit. Training a bias-free and normalized model is another challenge that needs to be tackled by regularization approaches.
3. "Did someone say graphs?!" Plotting is an important step to communicate your results, but the choice of plot is also very important as there are many ways in which you can tell the same story. Sometimes it becomes a challenge to select the right type of graph/plot.
column51:
1. My undergraduate degree is in computer science engineering, where I studied algorithms, data structures, discrete maths and programming. It prepared me as a software engineer.
2. My masters degree is in data science and machine learning. Since it was a research based degree, it prepared me as a data scientist, researcher and statistician.
3. I have taught data science and programming to undergrad and graduate students at two of the best universities in Australia - University of Melbourne and Monash University. This experience helped me in developing my communication and story-telling skills.
column52:
1. Interaction between engineering and business teams could be hard. It's hard to explain the technical nuances to business team. I counter this by telling relatable examples woven in an easy-to-follow story.

2. Keeping up with the regular developer sprints is hard for an applied data scientist as research can take longer time than standard coding and bug-fixing. I counter this by arranging separate meetings with stake holders.
